Last year, Elon Musk offered to buy Twitter Inc. for about $44 billion, whi=
ch required him to find $44 billion.=C2=A0Much of Musk=E2=80=99s money is t=
ied up in shares of Tesla Inc., where he is chief executive officer, so he =
sold some Tesla shares to raise some of the money. For a while, his plan wa=
s to get some more of the money by borrowing against his remaining Tesla st=
ake. He went and got commitment letters from a group of banks who  agreed t=
o lend him $12.5 billion, secured by $62.5 billion of Tesla stock. This was=
 going to be a margin loan: If the price of Tesla stock dropped too much, M=
usk would have to post more cash or sell Tesla shares to repay some of the =
loan. This was a bit risky, and in fact Tesla fell by about 30% between the=
 time Musk got the commitment letter and the time he closed the Twitter dea=
l. That was in part because of the Twitter deal: It was obviously a distrac=
tion for Musk, and his sales of Tesla stock to pay for Twitter also drove d=
own the price.
This made the margin loan less attractive, and ultimately  Musk called it o=
ff: He raised money from outside investors and sold more Tesla stock to avo=
id having to borrow against his Tesla stock.=C2=A0
Musk is very rich, but he is not=C2=A0that=C2=A0liquid: Most of his wealth =
consists of equity stakes in his various companies, not just Tesla but also=
=C2=A0Boring Co., Space Exploration Technologies Corp., Neuralink and, now,=
 Twitter, or I guess X. Of those companies, only Tesla is publicly traded; =
he can sell Tesla shares to raise cash, or borrow against them, and he has =
done both. (He never did the Twitter-related margin loan, but as of this Ma=
rch, out of his roughly 411 million Tesla shares, 238.4 million were =E2=80=
=9Cpledged as collateral to secure certain personal indebtedness.=E2=80=9D)=
 But there are downsides to using Tesla shares to raise money: They are vol=
atile, and his sales and borrowings are subject to public disclosure.
Meanwhile SpaceX is  worth like $150 billion and Musk owns about 42% of it,=
 making it the second-biggest source of his wealth behind Tesla. Borrowing =
against SpaceX stock is in some ways more attractive than borrowing against=
 Tesla stock: It requires less public disclosure,=C2=A0and because the stoc=
k doesn=E2=80=99t trade publicly it can=E2=80=99t really go down and trigge=
r margin calls.
On the other hand, if you go to a bank and ask to borrow billions of dollar=
s against an illiquid stake in a private company that you control, the bank=
 might be nervous. Oh, sure, if you=E2=80=99re Elon Musk, they=E2=80=99ll p=
robably find a way to do it, but it is not the most attractive deal for a b=
ank=E2=80=99s margin lending desk. Usually the margin lending desk will=C2=
=A0want=C2=A0to be able to make margin calls, and to seize and sell the sto=
ck if you don=E2=80=99t pay up; with the SpaceX stake that is harder.
So Musk found a more efficient lender against his SpaceX stake: SpaceX. The=
 Wall Street Journal reports:

Elon Musk tapped SpaceX, the rocket maker he oversees as chief executive, f=
or a $1 billion loan around the time he was acquiring the social-media comp=
any formerly known as Twitter.=C2=A0
The unusual loan is the latest example of how the world=E2=80=99s richest m=
an has drummed up cash from his empire of companies without having to perma=
nently part with shares, enabling him to raise funds for his wide array of =
endeavors.
SpaceX approved the loan, which was backed by some of his SpaceX stock, in =
October, and Musk drew all of it down the same month, according to document=
s reviewed by The Wall Street Journal.
It couldn=E2=80=99t be determined why he took on the debt. He paid the loan=
 back shortly after he borrowed the money, returning $1 billion with intere=
st to SpaceX in November. Musk and SpaceX didn=E2=80=99t respond to request=
s for comment. =E2=80=A6
The $1 billion loan temporarily shifted a significant chunk of capital for =
SpaceX, which is intertwined with many of the most important space missions=
 at the National Aeronautics and Space Administration and the Pentagon, to =
its top leader. SpaceX had $4.7 billion in cash and securities on hand at t=
he end of last year, the documents showed. The loan represented 11% of the =
$9 billion in equity the company reported selling since 2009, according to =
regulatory filings.

Is it=C2=A0best=C2=A0practices for a company to lend its CEO $1 billion sec=
ured by his own stock in the company? Oh no. But it=E2=80=99s Elon Musk. Al=
so this was a short-term bridge loan until he could raise more cash elsewhe=
re, and everything worked out fine.
Back in 2018, when Musk was musing about taking Tesla private,  I argued th=
at it made no sense: The public markets had been very kind to Tesla, allowi=
ng Musk to raise billions of dollars and giving his company a huge valuatio=
n without actually imposing any real restrictions on him. He complained abo=
ut short sellers, and about the short-term focus of public shareholders, bu=
t Tesla=E2=80=99s huge valuation without (at that point) any profits sugges=
ted that=C2=A0Tesla=E2=80=99s=C2=A0shareholders took the long view. =E2=80=
=9CAs a public company, we are subject to wild swings in our stock price th=
at can be a major distraction for everyone working at Tesla,=E2=80=9D wrote=
 Musk, but they don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0have=C2=A0to be: You can just not look a=
t the stock price; going private is an extreme way to impose that disciplin=
e.
But I think I may have missed the main issue. The main issue is that Musk r=
uns a web of companies, some of which need cash and some of which have cash=
, and he is also in the business of starting or buying other companies, cre=
ating more cash needs. If all of the companies are private, he can sort of =
use their cash interchangeably: Sure, each company has different outside in=
vestors and its own board of directors, but they are all part of the Elon M=
usk family, and it=E2=80=99s not too hard to work something out. Musk goes =
to the SpaceX board, he says =E2=80=9CI need to borrow $1 billion to buy Tw=
itter and save humanity,=E2=80=9D they are like =E2=80=9Cyour mission to sa=
ve humanity is why we love you and why we are on the board, here you go,=E2=
=80=9D and it=E2=80=99s fine. Probably he pays the loan back promptly with =
interest and everything is fine, but even if for some reason he couldn=E2=
=80=99t do that, probably SpaceX=E2=80=99s board and investors would unders=
tand. They love Musk and trust him completely.
Tesla=E2=80=99s board and investors are pretty similar =E2=80=94=C2=A0they =
are famously deferential to Musk =E2=80=94=C2=A0but there are=C2=A0some=C2=
=A0limits from being public. When Tesla bought another company in the Musk =
web (SolarCity), and when it agreed to pay him a gigantic compensation pack=
age, shareholders sued, claiming that Tesla=E2=80=99s board violated its fi=
duciary duties to outside shareholders. Musk  won the SolarCity case=C2=A0(=
the compensation one is ongoing), and his actual behavior does not seem to =
be all that constrained by being a public-company CEO, but still. This stuf=
f just doesn=E2=80=99t come up with his private companies. None of those sh=
areholders are going to sue him for lending himself $1 billion. If you want=
 to run a web of companies that all support each other, it might be easier =
if they are private.

