   =20
      AMC
   =20
 =20

We have   talked a   lot about the AMC APE story. Briefly, AMC Entertainmen=
t Holdings Inc. was a meme stock; its stock went way up for no particularly=
 good reason, and so it sold a bunch of shares to retail investors to raise=
 money to pay down debt and buy a   gold mine. Eventually it ran out of sto=
ck and asked its investors to authorize more, but the shareholders wouldn=
=E2=80=99t vote to authorize more shares, due to some combination of (1) no=
t wanting any more dilution and (2) being retail shareholders who don=E2=80=
=99t generally vote on anything. AMC decided to get around this problem by =
issuing a new class of preferred stock called AMC Preferred Equity Units, o=
r APEs, which had the same economic and voting rights as common shares. The=
n AMC held a vote to convert the APEs into common stock,   the APEs got to =
vote on the proposal, and it passed. (There was also a reverse stock split =
in which 10 shares would become one share.) Shareholders sued and AMC event=
ually settled by agreeing to give common shareholders a extra shares: Basic=
ally 750 old common shares become 85 new common shares (after the reverse s=
plit and settlement), while 750 old APEs become 75 new common shares.
There was further fighting over the settlement, but ultimately it was appro=
ved and, last month,  it happened: On Aug. 25, the stock split and APE conv=
ersion happened, and on Aug. 28 AMC delivered the extra shares to common sh=
areholders. And today AMC finally was able to get back to doing what it doe=
s best,  selling stock to retail investors:
On September 6, 2023, AMC Entertainment Holdings,=C2=A0Inc. (the =E2=80=9CC=
ompany=E2=80=9D) entered into an equity distribution agreement (the =E2=80=
=9CEquity Distribution Agreement=E2=80=9D) with Citigroup Global Markets In=
c., Barclays Capital Inc., B. Riley Securities, Inc., and Goldman Sachs & C=
o. LLC as sales agents (each, a =E2=80=9CSales Agent=E2=80=9D and collectiv=
ely, the =E2=80=9CSales Agents=E2=80=9D), to sell up to 40,000,000 shares o=
f Class=C2=A0A common stock, par value $0.01 per share, of the Company (the=
 =E2=80=9CCommon Stock=E2=80=9D), from time to time, through an =E2=80=9Cat=
-the-market=E2=80=9D offering program.
The APEs were outstanding for about a year, and during that time the   APE =
arbitrage was a big trade: The APEs consistently traded at a discount to th=
e common shares, so you could buy one APE for a little money, sell one comm=
on share short for more money, pocket the difference, and eventually close =
out the position when the APEs converted into common shares. This seemed li=
ke a good idea at the time, but it ended up being a horrible trade for some=
 of the people who did it: The cost of borrowing AMC stock was high, and yo=
u needed to keep your short position on for an unexpectedly=C2=A0long time,=
 so   for some traders the cost of borrowing more than ate up all their pro=
fits. (Also the APEs ended up not=C2=A0quite=C2=A0converting into common st=
ock at a 1-to-1 ratio, due to the lawsuit settlement.)=C2=A0
I will say, though, that the retail shareholders who worried about dilution=
 were =E2=80=A6=C2=A0right? Right-ish? Last August, when the APEs were firs=
t issued, they closed at $6 per APE on their first day, whereas the common =
stock closed at $10.46. I assumed there would eventually be a convergence, =
at least when the APEs converted into common, if not sooner: Ultimately all=
 of AMC=E2=80=99s share types would end up being worth somewhere between th=
e $6 APE floor and the $10.46 common-stock ceiling.=C2=A0
In fact, as of noon today AMC=E2=80=99s single class of common stock was tr=
ading at about $10.11 per share. Except of course that AMC did a 1-for-10 r=
everse stock split last month; on an apples-to-apples split-adjusted basis,=
 the common stock has gone from $104.60 to $10.11.
  [1]
 The common stock today is worth roughly 80% less than the=C2=A0APEs=C2=A0w=
ere worth last summer, and roughly 90% less than what the common was worth.=
=C2=A0
In 2021, when AMC was almost out of authorized shares to sell (but before i=
t came up with the APEs),   I joked:
I hope that after it completes this offering, AMC announces =E2=80=9Cokay t=
here is one more AMC share that we can sell, who wants it?=E2=80=9D And the=
n sells it for, like, $69 million. Is The Last AMC Share a non-fungible tok=
en? I mean, not really, in the sense that it is perfectly fungible with eve=
ry other AMC share. But if you buy The Last AMC Share you can make sure eve=
ryone knows about it, and AMC will probably give you a gold-plated bag of p=
opcorn and a statue of a gorilla to go with your Last Share. It=E2=80=99s a=
s good as an NFT. It is also much, much funnier than most of the actual NFT=
 projects. Really I see no reason AMC shouldn=E2=80=99t do this.
In the event AMC came up with a=C2=A0more=C2=A0creative way=C2=A0to get mor=
e shares to sell, but it tanked the share price, and now I think that my jo=
ke was a good idea. At least in June 2021, AMC=E2=80=99s stock was not trad=
ing primarily based on market expectations about its future cash flows; it =
was trading as a meme, an online community of investors who liked the stock=
 and dreamed of squeezing short sellers. They had diamond hands, and they w=
anted AMC to have diamond hands too: They weren=E2=80=99t selling stock, so=
 why should AMC?
Of course AMC was selling stock because (1) it needed the money and (2) the=
 meme-stock investors wanted to buy stock at irrationally high prices. But =
those are not great answers to give to meme-stock investors. The=C2=A0obvio=
us=C2=A0way to capitalize on meme-stock investor interest is to just sell t=
hem a lot of stock, but if you do that too aggressively they will lose inte=
rest and turn on you.=C2=A0

 =20
   =20
      TRAs
   =20
 =20

We   talked last week about tax receivable=C2=A0agreements. A lot of invest=
ment management firms are organized as private partnerships: The firm does =
not pay any tax, but its partners pay tax on their share of its income. Whe=
n they go public, these firms tend to turn into corporations (which pay cor=
porate tax), because that is generally easier for public shareholders. Ofte=
n the way they do this is with an =E2=80=9CUp-C=E2=80=9D structure, in whic=
h the firm keeps the partnership around but creates a new corporation to be=
 its parent company. Public shareholders buy shares in the parent corporati=
on, but the original partners =E2=80=94 generally, the founders and executi=
ves running the firm =E2=80=94=C2=A0remain partners of the partnership. The=
y can convert their partnership shares into corporate shares, and they will=
 have to do that if they want to=C2=A0sell, but there is no need to do it a=
ll at once.
Generally, when they convert their partnership units into corporate shares,=
 the executives have to pay taxes: The conversion is a taxable transaction,=
 and the value of the shares that they get is income to them.
  [2]
=C2=A0But there is an offsetting benefit: The=C2=A0company=C2=A0gets to red=
uce its taxes because of the conversion. Loosely speaking, the company gets=
 to amortize the value of the shares it issues against its income over 15 y=
ears.
  [3]
 So the partners have taxable income from their conversion, but the company=
 has a roughly offsetting tax savings.
This might seem a bit unfair to the executives: They pay taxes and the comp=
any saves on taxes. The executives are in charge, and not generally motivat=
ed by altruism, so they are not really going to take the company public in =
a way that is economically bad for them. So the norm in these deals is for =
the company to enter into a tax receivable agreement with the executives in=
 which it promises to pay them 85% of any tax savings it gets from their co=
nversions. The executives convert their shares whenever they want, they pay=
 taxes on conversion, and then the company saves on taxes over the next 15 =
years and sends them checks for 85% of those savings.
The TRA is an asset for the executives, though an odd sort of asset: If the=
y haven=E2=80=99t converted any shares yet, it represents a contingent righ=
t to receive some stream of payments starting whenever they convert their s=
hares and continuing for 15 years, with the actual payment depending on the=
 company=E2=80=99s taxable income. (If it does not have taxable income, it =
can=E2=80=99t use any tax deductions, so it doesn=E2=80=99t make any TRA pa=
yments.) Also any time the executives=C2=A0do=C2=A0convert their shares, th=
ey have to pay taxes; the TRA is not just free money but a contingent=C2=A0=
asset that offsets their contingent liability.
Still it=E2=80=99s an asset, and if you want to take the TRA=C2=A0away=C2=
=A0from the executives you have to pay them for it. We talked about this la=
st week in the context of Sculptor Capital Management Inc., which has a big=
 TRA with its founder Daniel Och, and which is now trying to sell itself. A=
 sale will trigger certain changes to the TRA, and might even end Sculptor=
=E2=80=99s partnership and cash Och out of his units, and he basically want=
s to get paid well for these changes.
More generally, companies sometimes want to get rid of their Up-C structure=
s and their TRAs for sort of corporate cleanliness purposes, and then the e=
xecutives ask =E2=80=9Cwell what=E2=80=99s in it for me,=E2=80=9D and the a=
nswer is a pile of money, and that can be awkward.  The Wall Street Journal=
 reports:

The founders of giant private-equity firms have been paid billions of dolla=
rs over the years. Payouts tied to arcane tax deals that brought nearly a b=
illion more are under scrutiny in a Delaware courtroom.
Private-equity titans Apollo Global Management and Carlyle Group paid insid=
ers more than $900 million as part of the tax deals. These second windfalls=
 have triggered litigation by investors alleging that the firms paid their =
founders for nothing in return. =E2=80=A6
The lawsuits involved so-called tax-receivable agreements, or TRAs. Firms w=
ith TRAs have a specific corporate structure that can create valuable tax a=
ssets for the company when founders and early investors sell their stakes a=
fter an initial public offering. Then the company and the sellers share the=
 tax asset so both benefit.
The private-equity firms=E2=80=99 restructurings didn=E2=80=99t create any =
tax assets, yet the company paid the founders anyway, the lawsuits say.=C2=
=A0

Here for instance is  the lawsuit against Apollo. Apollo was an Up-C public=
 company whose founders =C2=A0owned a lot of partnership units and had a TR=
A. The TRA did not pay them all that much, because they mostly held on to t=
heir partnership units and did not convert them. From the complaint:
[Co-founder Leon] Black had not engaged in any taxable exchanges of units s=
ince Apollo=E2=80=99s 2011 IPO. Black obtained liquidity by the more tax-ef=
ficient means of borrowing against his Apollo equity (rather than engaging =
in taxable exchanges). To the extent Black held Apollo equity until his dea=
th, his heirs would receive a tax-basis step up, which would complete the f=
amous =E2=80=9Cbuy, borrow, die=E2=80=9D tax-savings strategy.
But in 2021, as part of a governance overhaul that included Black leaving t=
he firm over his ties to Jeffrey Epstein, Apollo converted into a regular c=
orporation with a single share class. This conversion was done as a tax-fre=
e exchange: The founders got corporate shares=C2=A0without=C2=A0paying taxe=
s on the exchange, and without creating any tax benefits for Apollo. The TR=
A was no longer relevant. But to get the founders to agree to terminate the=
 TRA, Apollo had to pay them:=C2=A0

The largest of the three purported =E2=80=9Ccosts=E2=80=9D the Founders arg=
ued they would incur as a result of the windup of the Up-C structure was th=
e =E2=80=9CTRA Value Forgone.=E2=80=9D By design, the TRA only had value wh=
en the Founders engaged in taxable exchanges that created tax assets for th=
e Company. The Founders proposed that they be allowed to engage in tax-free=
 exchanges as part of the restructuring, which meant that no tax assets or =
tax savings would be created.=C2=A0
The Founders provided a calculation of purported forgone TRA value that ass=
umed that =E2=80=9Call Founder and Contributing Partner shares [would be] e=
xchanged today at the [redacted] share price.=E2=80=9D In other words, the =
Founders=E2=80=99 calculation of the foregone TRA value assumed that=C2=A0 =
that the founders would have=C2=A0immediately exchanged all of their units =
in taxable exchanges to create tax assets that would be usable for Apollo.

But they didn=E2=80=99t. The original deal was that they would pay taxes on=
 conversions, the company would get offsetting savings, and the company wou=
ld pay them 85% of those savings. The new deal was that they wouldn=E2=80=
=99t pay taxes on conversions, the company wouldn=E2=80=99t get offsetting =
savings, and the company would pay them 85% of its hypothetical savings und=
er the old deal anyway.
Or that is the claim. Eventually the deal was revised to=C2=A0pay them the =
same amount of money but with a different justification: They would sell so=
me of their partnership units to Apollo for $570 million in cash, and excha=
nge the rest for public-company shares. =E2=80=9CIt is inferable that the F=
ounders wanted the Challenged Payoff to be treated as consideration for a s=
ale of units in order to obtain favorable capital gains tax treatment,=E2=
=80=9D says the complaint. But it would be =E2=80=9Ca tax-free exchange of =
their remaining units for a number of shares equal to the number of units t=
he Founders held before they sold the initial slug of units for the Challen=
ged Payoff (i.e., as if the sale for the Challenged Payoff never happened)=
=E2=80=9D: They still converted all their partnership units into corporate =
shares,=C2=A0and=C2=A0got the=C2=A0$570 million in cash. They had a claim=
=E2=80=94=C2=A0the TRA =E2=80=94=C2=A0on the company, and they controlled t=
he company, and when they got rid of the TRA they made the company pay.

 =20
   =20
      Biodiversity
   =20
 =20

Last year   I mentioned a sort of postmodern finance novel by Ned Beauman c=
alled Venomous Lumpsucker.=C2=A0The premise of the book is that, in the nea=
r future, there is a market for =E2=80=9Cextinction credits,=E2=80=9D which=
 are sort of like carbon credits but for endangered species. The way carbon=
 credits work,   very roughly, is (1) you can get credits for=C2=A0not=C2=
=A0increasing the amount of carbon in the atmosphere and (2) you can sell t=
hose credits to someone else who=C2=A0does=C2=A0emit a lot of carbon, so=C2=
=A0they=C2=A0can feel good about themselves and tell their stakeholders tha=
t they have =E2=80=9Cnet zero=E2=80=9D emissions. (Their actual emissions, =
minus emissions that you did not do and that they paid you for, equal zero.=
) Beauman=E2=80=99s imagined extinction credits work the same way: You earn=
 credits for=C2=A0not=C2=A0causing any species to go extinct, and then you =
can sell those credits to other companies so that they=C2=A0can cause some =
species to go extinct with a good conscience. As with carbon credits =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0as with so many things =E2=80=94=C2=A0there are baseline measureme=
nt problems.
I thought of it today  because:

Biodiversity credits could be key to funding the conservation of the Earth=
=E2=80=99s ecosystems, but setting up a functioning market to buy and sell =
these payment tokens won=E2=80=99t be easy. =E2=80=A6 Credits act as tokens=
 that can be bought by companies and investors to fund restoration and cons=
ervation projects that, in theory, demonstrate positive outcomes for biodiv=
ersity. =E2=80=A6
Companies will eventually be asked to assess and reduce their impact on the=
 world=E2=80=99s natural systems, in line with agreements reached by govern=
ments at last year=E2=80=99s COP15 biodiversity conference. And this month,=
 a U.N.-backed framework will be published guiding business on how to repor=
t and act on nature-related risks such as deforestation, pollution, water s=
tress and over farming. However, the market for biocredits is likely to be =
voluntary at first, with no plans for a major regulated market on the lines=
 of the respected European Trading Scheme for carbon emissions.
=E2=80=9CI feel a bit of =E2=80=98carbon envy=E2=80=99 when I look at the c=
arbon markets,=E2=80=9D Cornell=E2=80=99s [Professor John Tobin-de la Puent=
e] said, noting that biodiversity markets lack a universal metric that can =
apply to every project, unlike carbon markets where each credit represents =
one metric ton of carbon dioxide.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9COne [biodiversity] project intends to conserve habitat, and they m=
easure their own success by the hectares of forest restored or set aside an=
d conserved,=E2=80=9D Tobin said. =E2=80=9CBut the next project down the ro=
ad, which also claims to be delivering biodiversity returns, what they=E2=
=80=99re interested in is preserving the hippo, or the rhino.=E2=80=9D

The baseline measurement problem with carbon is, roughly, you are a lumber =
company, and you own a bunch of trees, and if you chopped them down for lum=
ber you would make money but also increase the amount of carbon in the atmo=
sphere, and so carbon credits pay you for not chopping them down =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0but it is important to pay you against a reasonable baseline. If you =
wouldn=E2=80=99t have chopped them down anyway then you shouldn=E2=80=99t g=
et paid for not chopping them down. There are delicate issues.
Similarly if you run a rhino hunting lodge I suppose you should get biodive=
rsity credits for every rhino that you do not kill, but it does seem like t=
here are problems with that approach. Arguably the baseline number of extin=
ctions that you are supposed to cause is zero, making it hard to allocate c=
redit.

