10px;">
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">SpaceX</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Last year, Elon Musk offered to buy Twitter In=
c. for about $44 billion, which required him to find $44 billion.=C2=A0Much=
 of Musk=E2=80=99s money is tied up in shares of Tesla Inc., where he is ch=
ief executive officer, so he sold some Tesla shares to raise some of the mo=
ney. For a while, his plan was to get some more of the money by borrowing a=
gainst his remaining Tesla stake. He went and got commitment letters from a=
 group of banks who <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/32624846.227426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzL=
zIwMjItMDQtMjEvZWxvbi1nb3QtaGlzLW1vbmV5P2NtcGlkPUJCRDA5MDYyM19NT05FWVNUVUZG=
JnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDkwNiZ=
1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB824de53d" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 agreed to lend him $12.5 billion</a>, secured by $62.5 billion of Tesla st=
ock. This was going to be a margin loan: If the price of Tesla stock droppe=
d too much, Musk would have to post more cash or sell Tesla shares to repay=
 some of the loan. This was a bit risky, and in fact Tesla fell by about 30=
% between the time Musk got the commitment letter and the time he closed th=
e Twitter deal. That was in part <em>because </em>of the Twitter deal: It w=
as obviously a distraction for Musk, and his sales of Tesla stock to pay fo=
r Twitter also drove down the price.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This made the margin loan less attractive, and=
 ultimately <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/326248=
46.227426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItM=
DUtMjYvZWxvbi1jYWxsZWQtb2ZmLWhpcy1tYXJnaW4tbG9hbj9jbXBpZD1CQkQwOTA2MjNfTU9O=
RVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0=
yMzA5MDYmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBadfbec34"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;"> Musk called it off</a>: He raised money from outside investors an=
d sold more Tesla stock to avoid having to borrow against his Tesla stock.=
=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Musk is very rich, but he is not=C2=A0<em>that=
=C2=A0</em>liquid: Most of his wealth consists of equity stakes in his vari=
ous companies, not just Tesla but also=C2=A0Boring Co., Space Exploration T=
echnologies Corp., Neuralink and, now, Twitter, or I guess X. Of those comp=
anies, only Tesla is publicly traded; he can sell Tesla shares to raise cas=
h, or borrow against them, and he has done both. (He never did the Twitter-=
related margin loan, but as of this March, out of his roughly 411 million T=
esla shares, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32624=
846.227426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEv=
MTMxODYwNS8wMDAxMTkzMTI1MjMwOTQwNzUvZDQ1MTM0MmRkZWYxNGEuaHRtI3RvYzQ1MTM0Ml8=
1OQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB35b32ddb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">238.4 million</a> were =E2=
=80=9Cpledged as collateral to secure certain personal indebtedness.=E2=80=
=9D) But there are downsides to using Tesla shares to raise money: They are=
 volatile, and his sales and borrowings are subject to public disclosure.</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile SpaceX is <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32624846.227426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJn=
LmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDYtMjMvc3BhY2V4LXRlbmRlci1vZmZlci1zYWlkLXR=
vLXZhbHVlLWNvbXBhbnktYXQtYWJvdXQtMTUwLWJpbGxpb24_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDkwNjIzX01PTk=
VZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09M=
jMwOTA2JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3951f51a" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;"> worth like $150 billion</a> and Musk owns about 42% of it, making =
it the second-biggest source of his wealth behind Tesla. Borrowing against =
SpaceX stock is in some ways more attractive than borrowing against Tesla s=
tock: It requires less public disclosure,=C2=A0and because the stock doesn=
=E2=80=99t trade publicly it can=E2=80=99t really go down and trigger margi=
n calls.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand, if you go to a bank and ask=
 to borrow billions of dollars against an illiquid stake in a private compa=
ny that you control, the bank might be nervous. Oh, sure, if you=E2=80=99re=
 Elon Musk, they=E2=80=99ll probably find a way to do it, but it is not the=
 most attractive deal for a bank=E2=80=99s margin lending desk. Usually the=
 margin lending desk will=C2=A0want=C2=A0to be able to make margin calls, a=
nd to seize and sell the stock if you don=E2=80=99t pay up; with the SpaceX=
 stake that is harder.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So Musk found a more efficient lender against =
his SpaceX stake: SpaceX. The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusines=
s.com/click/32624846.227426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9idXNpbmVzcy9lbG9uLW1=
1c2stc3BhY2V4LWxvYW4tMjY5YTIxNjg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9cb29925" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
>Wall Street Journal reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Elon Musk tapped SpaceX, the rocket maker he o=
versees as chief executive, for a $1 billion loan around the time he was ac=
quiring the social-media company formerly known as Twitter.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The unusual loan is the latest example of how =
the world=E2=80=99s richest man has drummed up cash from his empire of comp=
anies without having to permanently part with shares, enabling him to raise=
 funds for his wide array of endeavors.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">SpaceX approved the loan, which was backed by =
some of his SpaceX stock, in October, and Musk drew all of it down the same=
 month, according to documents reviewed by The Wall Street Journal.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It couldn=E2=80=99t be determined why he took =
on the debt. He paid the loan back shortly after he borrowed the money, ret=
urning $1 billion with interest to SpaceX in November. Musk and SpaceX didn=
=E2=80=99t respond to requests for comment. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The $1 billion loan temporarily shifted a sign=
ificant chunk of capital for SpaceX, which is intertwined with many of the =
most important space missions at the National Aeronautics and Space Adminis=
tration and the Pentagon, to its top leader. SpaceX had $4.7 billion in cas=
h and securities on hand at the end of last year, the documents showed. The=
 loan represented 11% of the $9 billion in equity the company reported sell=
ing since 2009, according to regulatory filings.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Is it=C2=A0<em>best=C2=A0</em>practices for a =
company to lend its CEO $1 billion secured by his own stock in the company?=
 Oh no. But it=E2=80=99s Elon Musk. Also this was a short-term bridge loan =
until he could raise more cash elsewhere, and everything worked out fine.</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Back in 2018, when Musk was musing about takin=
g Tesla private, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3=
2624846.227426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIw=
MTgtMDgtMTMvZnVuZGluZy1mb3ItZWxvbi1tdXNrLXMtdGVzbGEtYnV5b3V0LXdhc24tdC1zby1=
zZWN1cmU_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDkwNjIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc2=
91cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwOTA2JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfe9a4406" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> I argued</a> that it made no se=
nse: The public markets had been very kind to Tesla, allowing Musk to raise=
 billions of dollars and giving his company a huge valuation without actual=
ly imposing any real restrictions on him. He complained about short sellers=
, and about the short-term focus of public shareholders, but Tesla=E2=80=99=
s huge valuation without (at that point) any profits suggested that=C2=A0<e=
m>Tesla=E2=80=99s=C2=A0</em>shareholders took the long view. =E2=80=9CAs a =
public company, we are subject to wild swings in our stock price that can b=
e a major distraction for everyone working at Tesla,=E2=80=9D wrote Musk, b=
ut they don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>have=C2=A0</em>to be: You can just not look =
at the stock price; going private is an extreme way to impose that discipli=
ne.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But I think I may have missed the main issue. =
The main issue is that Musk runs a web of companies, some of which need cas=
h and some of which have cash, and he is also in the business of starting o=
r buying other companies, creating more cash needs. If all of the companies=
 are private, he can sort of use their cash interchangeably: Sure, each com=
pany has different outside investors and its own board of directors, but th=
ey are all part of the Elon Musk family, and it=E2=80=99s not too hard to w=
ork something out. Musk goes to the SpaceX board, he says =E2=80=9CI need t=
o borrow $1 billion to buy Twitter and save humanity,=E2=80=9D they are lik=
e =E2=80=9Cyour mission to save humanity is why we love you and why we are =
on the board, here you go,=E2=80=9D and it=E2=80=99s fine. Probably he pays=
 the loan back promptly with interest and everything is fine, but even if f=
or some reason he couldn=E2=80=99t do that, probably SpaceX=E2=80=99s board=
 and investors would understand. They love Musk and trust him completely.</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Tesla=E2=80=99s board and investors are pretty=
 similar =E2=80=94=C2=A0they are famously deferential to Musk =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0but there are=C2=A0<em>some=C2=A0</em>limits from being public. When Tes=
la bought another company in the Musk web (SolarCity), and when it agreed t=
o pay him a gigantic compensation package, shareholders sued, claiming that=
 Tesla=E2=80=99s board violated its fiduciary duties to outside shareholder=
s. Musk <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32624846.2=
27426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDQtM=
jgvZWxvbi1tdXNrLXMtb3RoZXItbWVyZ2VyLXdvcmtlZC1vdXQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDkwNjIzX01P=
TkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm0=
9MjMwOTA2JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa0bb76ca=
" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-colo=
r: #ccc;"> won the SolarCity case</a>=C2=A0(the <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32624846.227426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5jb=
20vMjAyMi8xMS8xNi9idXNpbmVzcy9lbG9uLW11c2stdGVzbGEtZGVsYXdhcmUtY291cnQuaHRt=
bA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc622f982" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">compensation one</a> is ongoi=
ng), and his actual behavior does not seem to be all that constrained by be=
ing a public-company CEO, but still. This stuff just doesn=E2=80=99t come u=
p with his private companies. None of those shareholders are going to sue h=
im for lending himself $1 billion. If you want to run a web of companies th=
at all support each other, it might be easier if they are private.</p>
