<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/32624846.227426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDgtMzAvc2N1bHB0b3ItaXMtZnVsbC1vZi1jb25mbGljdHM_Y21waWQ9=
QkJEMDkwNjIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR=
0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwOTA2JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cB569398aa" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;">  talked last week</a> about tax receivable=C2=A0=
agreements. A lot of investment management firms are organized as private p=
artnerships: The firm does not pay any tax, but its partners pay tax on the=
ir share of its income. When they go public, these firms tend to turn into =
corporations (which pay corporate tax), because that is generally easier fo=
r public shareholders. Often the way they do this is with an =E2=80=9CUp-C=
=E2=80=9D structure, in which the firm keeps the partnership around but cre=
ates a new corporation to be its parent company. Public shareholders buy sh=
ares in the parent corporation, but the original partners =E2=80=94 general=
ly, the founders and executives running the firm =E2=80=94=C2=A0remain part=
ners of the partnership. They can convert their partnership shares into cor=
porate shares, and they will have to do that if they want to=C2=A0<em>sell<=
/em>, but there is no need to do it all at once.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Generally, when they convert their partnership=
 units into corporate shares, the executives have to pay taxes: The convers=
ion is a taxable transaction, and the value of the shares that they get is =
income to them.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgrou=
nd-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0But there is an offsetting benefit: The=C2=A0<em>company=C2=A0</e=
m>gets to reduce its taxes because of the conversion. Loosely speaking, the=
 company gets to amortize the value of the shares it issues against its inc=
ome over 15 years.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backg=
round-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a> So the partners have taxable income from their conversion, but the com=
pany has a roughly offsetting tax savings.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This might seem a bit unfair to the executives=
: They pay taxes and the company saves on taxes. The executives are in char=
ge, and not generally motivated by altruism, so they are not really going t=
o take the company public in a way that is economically bad for them. So th=
e norm in these deals is for the company to enter into a tax receivable agr=
eement with the executives in which it promises to pay them 85% of any tax =
savings it gets from their conversions. The executives convert their shares=
 whenever they want, they pay taxes on conversion, and then the company sav=
es on taxes over the next 15 years and sends them checks for 85% of those s=
avings.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The TRA is an asset for the executives, though=
 an odd sort of asset: If they haven=E2=80=99t converted any shares yet, it=
 represents a contingent right to receive some stream of payments starting =
whenever they convert their shares and continuing for 15 years, with the ac=
tual payment depending on the company=E2=80=99s taxable income. (If it does=
 not have taxable income, it can=E2=80=99t use any tax deductions, so it do=
esn=E2=80=99t make any TRA payments.) Also any time the executives=C2=A0<em=
>do=C2=A0</em>convert their shares, they have to pay taxes; the TRA is not =
just free money but a contingent=C2=A0asset that offsets their contingent l=
iability.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still it=E2=80=99s an asset, and if you want t=
o take the TRA=C2=A0<em>away=C2=A0</em>from the executives you have to pay =
them for it. We talked about this last week in the context of Sculptor Capi=
tal Management Inc., which has a big TRA with its founder Daniel Och, and w=
hich is now trying to sell itself. A sale will trigger certain changes to t=
he TRA, and might even end Sculptor=E2=80=99s partnership and cash Och out =
of his units, and he basically wants to get paid well for these changes.</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">More generally, companies sometimes want to ge=
t rid of their Up-C structures and their TRAs for sort of corporate cleanli=
ness purposes, and then the executives ask =E2=80=9Cwell what=E2=80=99s in =
it for me,=E2=80=9D and the answer is a pile of money, and that can be awkw=
ard. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32624846.2274=
26/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9maW5hbmNlL21vbmV5LWZvci1ub3RoaW5nLWxhd3N1aXRz=
LWFnYWluc3QtcHJpdmF0ZS1lcXVpdHktZm91bmRlcnMtZ2V0LWJvb3N0LTM3YTU4ZGI2/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cB505bae44" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> The Wall Street Journal reports</a>:<=
/p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The founders of giant private-equity firms hav=
e been paid billions of dollars over the years. Payouts tied to arcane tax =
deals that brought nearly a billion more are under scrutiny in a Delaware c=
ourtroom.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Private-equity titans Apollo Global Management=
 and Carlyle Group paid insiders more than $900 million as part of the tax =
deals. These second windfalls have triggered litigation by investors allegi=
ng that the firms paid their founders for nothing in return. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The lawsuits involved so-called tax-receivable=
 agreements, or TRAs. Firms with TRAs have a specific corporate structure t=
hat can create valuable tax assets for the company when founders and early =
investors sell their stakes after an initial public offering. Then the comp=
any and the sellers share the tax asset so both benefit.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The private-equity firms=E2=80=99 restructurin=
gs didn=E2=80=99t create any tax assets, yet the company paid the founders =
anyway, the lawsuits say.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here for instance is <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32624846.227426/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5=
pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3JuUDkxdTk0ZVNuNC92MA/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cB7162098c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the lawsuit against Apollo</a>. Apollo was=
 an Up-C public company whose founders =C2=A0owned a lot of partnership uni=
ts and had a TRA. The TRA did not pay them all that much, because they most=
ly held on to their partnership units and did not convert them. From the co=
mplaint:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[Co-founder Leon] Black had not en=
gaged in any taxable exchanges of units since Apollo=E2=80=99s 2011 IPO. Bl=
ack obtained liquidity by the more tax-efficient means of borrowing against=
 his Apollo equity (rather than engaging in taxable exchanges). To the exte=
nt Black held Apollo equity until his death, his heirs would receive a tax-=
basis step up, which would complete the famous =E2=80=9Cbuy, borrow, die=E2=
=80=9D tax-savings strategy.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But in 2021, as part of a governance overhaul =
that included Black leaving the firm over his ties to Jeffrey Epstein, Apol=
lo converted into a regular corporation with a single share class. This con=
version was done as a tax-free exchange: The founders got corporate shares=
=C2=A0<em>without=C2=A0</em>paying taxes on the exchange, and without creat=
ing any tax benefits for Apollo. The TRA was no longer relevant. But to get=
 the founders to agree to terminate the TRA, Apollo had to pay them:=C2=A0<=
/p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The largest of the three purported =E2=80=9Cco=
sts=E2=80=9D the Founders argued they would incur as a result of the windup=
 of the Up-C structure was the =E2=80=9CTRA Value Forgone.=E2=80=9D By desi=
gn, the TRA only had value when the Founders engaged in taxable exchanges t=
hat created tax assets for the Company. The Founders proposed that they be =
allowed to engage in tax-free exchanges as part of the restructuring, which=
 meant that no tax assets or tax savings would be created.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Founders provided a calculation of purport=
ed forgone TRA value that assumed that =E2=80=9Call Founder and Contributin=
g Partner shares [would be] exchanged today at the [<em>redacted</em>] shar=
e price.=E2=80=9D In other words, the Founders=E2=80=99 calculation of the =
foregone TRA value assumed that=C2=A0 that the founders would have=C2=A0<em=
>immediately </em>exchanged <em>all </em>of their units in <em>taxable </em=
>exchanges to create tax assets that would be usable for Apollo.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But they didn=E2=80=99t. The original deal was=
 that they would pay taxes on conversions, the company would get offsetting=
 savings, and the company would pay them 85% of those savings. The new deal=
 was that they wouldn=E2=80=99t pay taxes on conversions, the company would=
n=E2=80=99t get offsetting savings, and the company would pay them 85% of i=
ts hypothetical savings under the old deal anyway.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or that is the claim. Eventually the deal was =
revised to=C2=A0pay them the same amount of money but with a different just=
ification: They would sell some of their partnership units to Apollo for $5=
70 million in cash, and exchange the rest for public-company shares. =E2=80=
=9CIt is inferable that the Founders wanted the Challenged Payoff to be tre=
ated as consideration for a sale of units in order to obtain favorable capi=
tal gains tax treatment,=E2=80=9D says the complaint. But it would be =E2=
=80=9Ca tax-free exchange of their remaining units for a number of shares e=
qual to the number of units the Founders held <em>before </em>they sold the=
 initial slug of units for the Challenged Payoff (i.e., as if the sale for =
the Challenged Payoff never happened)=E2=80=9D: They still converted all th=
eir partnership units into corporate shares,=C2=A0<em>and=C2=A0</em>got the=
=C2=A0$570 million in cash. They had a claim=E2=80=94=C2=A0the TRA =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0on the company, and they controlled the company, and when they got=
 rid of the TRA they made the company pay.</p>
