<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Last year <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/32624846.227426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcG=
luaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDctMTIvaS13YXMtdG9sZC10aGVyZS1kLWJlLWEtY2FrZS1tZ=
XJnZXI_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDkwNjIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291=
cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwOTA2JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/60=
7f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf458e909" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsc=
ope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  I mentioned</a> a sort of postmo=
dern finance novel by Ned Beauman called <em><a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/32624846.227426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucGVuZ3VpbnJhbmRv=
bWhvdXNlLmNvbS9ib29rcy83MDk2MTQvdmVub21vdXMtbHVtcHN1Y2tlci1ieS1uZWQtYmVhdW1=
hbi8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB91e46ab8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Venomous Lumpsucker</a></em=
>.=C2=A0The premise of the book is that, in the near future, there is a mar=
ket for =E2=80=9Cextinction credits,=E2=80=9D which are sort of like carbon=
 credits but for endangered species. The way carbon credits work, <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32624846.227426/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDQtMjEveW91LWNhbi1z=
ZWxsLXRoZS10cmVlcy15b3UtZG9uLXQtY3V0P2NtcGlkPUJCRDA5MDYyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV=
0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDkwNiZ1dG=
1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB424f8c00" itemprop=3D=
"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  v=
ery roughly</a>, is (1) you can get credits for=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>incr=
easing the amount of carbon in the atmosphere and (2) you can sell those cr=
edits to someone else who=C2=A0<em>does=C2=A0</em>emit a lot of carbon, so=
=C2=A0<em>they=C2=A0</em>can feel good about themselves and tell their stak=
eholders that they have =E2=80=9Cnet zero=E2=80=9D emissions. (Their actual=
 emissions, minus emissions that you did not do and that they paid you for,=
 equal zero.) Beauman=E2=80=99s imagined extinction credits work the same w=
ay: You earn credits for=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>causing any species to go e=
xtinct, and then you can sell those credits to other companies so that they=
=C2=A0<em>can </em>cause some species to go extinct with a good conscience.=
 As with carbon credits =E2=80=94=C2=A0as with so many things =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0there are baseline measurement problems.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I thought of it today <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32624846.227426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS=
9hcnRpY2xlcy9iaW9jcmVkaXRzLWNvdWxkLWhlbHAtc2F2ZS10aGUtZWFydGgtYnV0LWEtbWFya=
2V0LWlzLXNvbWUtd2F5LW9mZi05MmI2MDkwYT9tb2Q9aXRwX3dzaiZydT15YWhvbw/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cB38a684d6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" ta=
rget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> because</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Biodiversity credits could be key to funding t=
he conservation of the Earth=E2=80=99s ecosystems, but setting up a functio=
ning market to buy and sell these payment tokens won=E2=80=99t be easy. =E2=
=80=A6 Credits act as tokens that can be bought by companies and investors =
to fund restoration and conservation projects that, in theory, demonstrate =
positive outcomes for biodiversity. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Companies will eventually be asked to assess a=
nd reduce their impact on the world=E2=80=99s natural systems, in line with=
 agreements reached by governments at last year=E2=80=99s COP15 biodiversit=
y conference. And this month, a U.N.-backed framework will be published gui=
ding business on how to report and act on nature-related risks such as defo=
restation, pollution, water stress and over farming. However, the market fo=
r biocredits is likely to be voluntary at first, with no plans for a major =
regulated market on the lines of the respected European Trading Scheme for =
carbon emissions.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CI feel a bit of =E2=80=98carbon envy=
=E2=80=99 when I look at the carbon markets,=E2=80=9D Cornell=E2=80=99s [Pr=
ofessor John Tobin-de la Puente] said, noting that biodiversity markets lac=
k a universal metric that can apply to every project, unlike carbon markets=
 where each credit represents one metric ton of carbon dioxide.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9COne [biodiversity] project intends to=
 conserve habitat, and they measure their own success by the hectares of fo=
rest restored or set aside and conserved,=E2=80=9D Tobin said. =E2=80=9CBut=
 the next project down the road, which also claims to be delivering biodive=
rsity returns, what they=E2=80=99re interested in is preserving the hippo, =
or the rhino.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The baseline measurement problem with carbon i=
s, roughly, you are a lumber company, and you own a bunch of trees, and if =
you chopped them down for lumber you would make money but also increase the=
 amount of carbon in the atmosphere, and so carbon credits pay you for not =
chopping them down =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it is important to pay you against a =
reasonable baseline. If you wouldn=E2=80=99t have chopped them down anyway =
then you shouldn=E2=80=99t get paid for not chopping them down. There are d=
elicate issues.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Similarly if you run a rhino hunting lodge I s=
uppose you should get biodiversity credits for every rhino that you do not =
kill, but it does seem like there are problems with that approach. Arguably=
 the baseline number of extinctions that you are supposed to cause is zero,=
 making it hard to allocate credit.</p>
